<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN BRIEF: SCIENCE / MEDICINE; 
</P>
<P>
DIURETIC, FEWER FRACTURES LINKED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Older people who take one variety of commonly used blood pressure pills called 
diuretics may reduce their risk of hip fractures by one-third, according to a 
study. The researchers found that people over 65 who used the type of diuretics 
known as thiazides appeared to suffer significantly fewer broken hips than 
nonusers. 
</P>
<P>
They said that if the medicines work the way they believe, up to 21,600 hip 
fractures might be avoided annually. However, they cautioned that more study 
will be needed before the drugs could be prescribed solely to prevent 
fractures. They said experts will have to be sure that the benefits of this 
treatment outweigh the potential hazards. 
</P>
<P>
Experts have long known that thiazides can prevent the body from losing 
calcium. However, the medicines can also have unwanted side effects, including 
potassium deficiency and high cholesterol. 
</P>
<P>
The study, directed by Dr. Andrea Z. LaCroix of the Group Health Cooperative of 
Puget Sound, Wash., was published in the New England Journal of Medicine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
