Home Affordability Gap Growing: Home prices rose faster than home buyers' 
incomes in 1989 for the 14th straight year, a new study concludes. 
</P>
<P>
The Chicago Title &amp; Trust Co. said its annual survey of home buyers also 
revealed that the majority of 1989 home buyers were two-income couples who 
saved for an average of 2.9 years for a down payment. Nationally, the median 
home price rose 6.4% to $129,800, while the median household income of 1989 
home buyers rose 6.3% to $58,700. Median home prices were highest in San 
Francisco at $199,900, followed by Los Angeles, $187,500, Orange County, 
$166,300, and New York City, $166,200. 
